# Background 
	
##Adiabatic Representation
A molecular Hamiltonian in the absence of an external field is constructed as the sum of electronic and nuclear Hamiltonians with the addition of an electron-nuclear Coulomb potential
	$
		\begin{matrix}
			H(r,R) = \overbrace{H_e(r)}^{T_e(r) + V_e(r)} +\overbrace{H_N(R)}^{T_N(R)+V_N(R)} +& V_{eN}(r,R),
			\\
			\\
			T_e(r) = -\sum_{i}^{n_e}\frac{\nabla_{e,i}^2}{2},
			\\
			\\
			V_e(r) = \sum_{i}^{n_e}\sum_{j>i}^{n_e}\frac{1}{|r_j-r_i|},
			\\
			\\
			T_N(R) = -\sum_{i}^{n_N}\frac{\nabla_{N,i}^2}{2M_i},
			\\
			\\
			V_N(R) = \sum_{i}^{n_N}\sum_{j>i}^{n_N}\frac{Z_jZ_i}{|R_j-R_i|},
			\\
			\\
			V_{en}(r,R) = -\sum_{i}^{n_N}\sum_{j}^{n_e}\frac{Z_i}{|r_j-R_i|}.
		\end{matrix}
$
	$T_e(r), V_e(r), T_N(R), V_N(R)$ and $V_{en}(r,R)$ are the electronic kinetic and potential operators, nuclear kinetic and potential operators, and electronic and nuclear interaction potential operator respectively.  
	$r$ and $R$ denote the electronic and nuclear degrees of freedom, while $n_e$ and $n_N$ are the number of electrons and nuclei in the system, and $M_i$, and $Z_i$ are the nuclear mass and charges.
	
	This molecular Hamiltonian satisfies the time-independent Schr\"odinger equation (TISE)
	\begin{equation}\label{eq:2.2}
					H(r,R)\Psi_k(r,R) = E_k\Psi_k(r,R).
	\end{equation}
	In the equation above, $\Psi_k(r, R)$ are the eigenfunctions of $H(r,R)$.
	When $H(r, R)$ is substituted into the time-independent Schr\"odinger equation $(\ref{eq:2.2})$ consists of coupled electronic-nuclear second order differential equations. At the moment, it is unfeasible to decouple the nuclear and electronic Hilbert spaces by separation of variables. Thus to decouple the electronic from nuclear degrees of freedom, approximative techniques are required.\cite{levine2013quantum} 
	
	One technique is to invoke the adiabatic theorem, where the nuclear time scale is considered static to the electronic counterparts. Here, the  Born-Oppenheimer representation is employed, where one introduces a  parameter for nuclear degrees of freedom in the electronic Hamiltonian,  such that\cite{Zur_Quantentheorie_der_Molekeln}
	
	\begin{equation}
		H_e(r|R) = T_e(r) + V_{e}(r) + V_{N}(R) +V_{eN}(r|R).
	\end{equation}
	The bar in $H_e(r|R)$ represents the parametric dependence of the electronic degrees of freedom on the nuclear. Because of this parametric dependence we can obtain eigenstates and eigenfunctions of the electronic Hamiltonian such that
	
	\begin{equation}
		H_e(r|R)\phi_l(r|R) = \epsilon_l(R)\phi_l(r|R).
	\end{equation}
	Here,  $\phi_l(r|R)$ are the  adiabatic electronic states, and $\epsilon_l(R)$, the electronic potential energy surfaces, which allows for a redefinition of the molecular Hamiltonian $(\ref{eq:2.2})$ to $H(r,R) = T_N(R) +H_e(r|R) $.
	Next, eigenfunctions of the  parameterized molecular Hamiltonian are written using the Born-Huang expansion
	
	\begin{equation}
		\psi_k(r) = \sum_{l}\chi_{lk}(R)\phi_l(r|R),
	\end{equation}
	where $\chi_{kl}$ are the nuclear expansion coefficients.\cite{Born_Huang} This ansatz is substituted in to the redefined  molecular Hamiltonian $(\ref{eq:2.2})$
	
	\begin{equation}\label{eq: 2.5}
		\begin{matrix}
		H(r,R)\psi_k(r,R) = \sum_{l}T_N\chi_{lk}\phi_l(r|R) + H_e(r|R)\chi_{lk}\phi_l(r|R) =
		\\
		\\
		H(r,R)\psi_k(r,R) = \sum_{l}T_N\chi_{lk}\phi_l(r|R) + \epsilon_l(R)\chi_{lk}\phi_l(r|R).
		\end{matrix}
	\end{equation}
	
	To obtain the non-adiabatic elements, we project $\phi(r|R)_m^*$ on the nuclear kinetic operators in $(\ref{eq: 2.5})$ then by inserting a resolution of identity with respect to  to the electronic adiabatic states arriving at
	
	
	\begin{equation}
		\begin{matrix}
			\bra{\phi_m(R)}T_N\ket{\phi_l(R)}_r\chi_{lk}  = & 
			\\
			-\sum_{i}\frac{1}{2M_i}\bigg(\delta_{ml}\nabla^2_{N,i}
			+\tau^{(i)}_{ml}(R)\nabla_{N,i} + \nabla_{N,i}\tau^{(i)}_{ml}(R) +
			\sum_{n}\tau^{(i)}_{mn}(R)\tau^{(i)}_{nl}(R)
			\bigg) \chi_{lk}.
		\end{matrix}
	\end{equation}
	Here, the anti-hermitian first order non-adiabatic coupling vectors are $\tau_{ml}^{(i)} =\braket{\phi_m(R)|\nabla_{N,i}\phi_l(R)}_r$, while the sum of products $-\sum_{n}\bigg(\sum_{i}\frac{1}{2M_{i}}\tau^{(i)}_{mn}(R)\tau^{(i)}_{nl}(R)\bigg)$ are the diagonal Born-Oppenheimer corrections (DBOC) when $m = l$.
	A useful transformation of $\tau_{ml}^{(i)}$, invokes the Hellman-Feynman theorem $\nabla_R\braket{\phi_m(R)|H_e(R)\phi_l(R)}_r =  \nabla_R\delta_{ml}\epsilon_m(R)$, and substitution of the electronic Hamiltonian $H_e(R)$. This is allows for one to observe the  first order non-adiabatic coupling vectors reliance on the energy gap difference of the two degenerate electronic energy surfaces
	
	\begin{equation}\label{eq:2.8}
		\begin{matrix}
			\nabla_R\braket{\phi_m(R)|H_e(R)|\phi_l(R)}_r = 0,\space \text{when $m\neq l$}.
			\\
			\\
			 \braket{\nabla_R\phi_m(R)|H_e(R)|\phi_l(R)}_r + \braket{\phi_m(R)|\nabla_RH_e(R)|\phi_l(R)}_r +\braket{\phi_m(R)|H_e(R)|\nabla_R\phi_l(R)}_r =0,
			 \\
			 \\
			 \braket{\nabla_R\phi_m(R)|\phi_l(R)}_r\epsilon_l(R) + \braket{\phi_m(R)|\nabla_RH_e(R)|\phi_l(R)}_r +\epsilon_m(R)\braket{\phi_m(R)|\nabla_R\phi_m(R)} _r=0.
			 
		\end{matrix}
	\end{equation}
	Rearranging $(\ref{eq:2.8})$ and replacing the subscript $\nabla_R$ with $\nabla_{N,i}$, denoting individual nuclear coordinates, 
	
	\begin{equation}\label{eq:2.9}
		\tau^{(i)}_{ml}(R) = \braket{\phi_m(R)|\nabla_{N,i}\phi_l(R)}
		=
		\frac{\bra{\phi_m(R)}\nabla_{N,i} H_e(R)\ket{\phi_l(R)}_r}{\epsilon_l(R) - \epsilon_m(R)}.
	\end{equation}\cite{On_Nonadiabatic_Dynamical_Simulations_near_Conical_Intersections_via_Surface_hopping_Methods}
	
	
	 The adiabatic representation accurately describes quantum molecular dynamics in regions absent from potential energy surface intersections. This is a consequence of the presence of non-adiabatic coupling terms $\tau_{mn}^{(i)}$, which become singular in these regions due to their inverse electronic energy gap dependence $(\epsilon_n(R) - \epsilon_m(R))$. Thus to calculate the $\tau_{mn}^{(i)}$'s advanced analytical gradient techniques are needed, which scale exponentially with the number of orbitals used in the electronic structure method.\cite{TNAC} Consequently, one generally searches for a different ansatz to expand the molecular Hamiltonian in.\cite{Anal_Nac}
	 
	 Using this formalism, the molecular Hamiltonian takes the form of 
	
	\begin{equation}
		\sum_{l}
		\big[T_N\delta_{ml} + \epsilon_m(R)\delta_{ml} +\Lambda_{ml}(R)]\chi_{lk}(R) =E_k\chi_{mk}(R),
	\end{equation}
	with all non-adiabatic effects condensed in to the operator  $\Lambda_{ml}$,
	
	\begin{equation}
		\Lambda_{ml} = -\sum_{i}\frac{1}{2M_i}\bigg(
		\tau^{(i)}_{ml}(R)\nabla_{N,i} + \nabla_{N,i}\tau^{(i)}_{ml}(R) +
		\sum_{n}\tau^{(i)}_{mn}(R)\tau^{(i)}_{nl}(R)
		\bigg).
	\end{equation}
	If all $\tau^{(i)}_{mn}(R)$ are negligible, inferring that electronic potential energy differences are significant, one may ignore  $\Lambda_{ml}$. By doing so,  the Born-Oppenheimer equation is realized
	
	\begin{equation}
		\sum_{l}\big(T_N\delta_{ml} + \epsilon_l(R)\delta_{ml}\big)\chi_{lk}(R)=E_k\chi_{mk}(R).
	\end{equation} 
	
	\section{Diabatic Representation}
	
	
	As the $\tau_{ml}$ elements are divergent in regions of quasi or exact degeneracy, 
	the question arises if one can rotate the Hamiltonian to some basis where the derivative couplings $\tau^{(i)}_{mn} = 0$. If possible, all non-adiabatic effects will be encapsulated in the potential matrix.\cite{Beyond_Born_Oppenheimer} As Mead and Truhlar proved in the 1980's, this is generally not the case, but the creation of so called  \textit{quasi-diabatic states }exist, where the minimization  of $\tau^{(i)}_{mn}$ , can be done.\cite{Conditions_for_the_definition_of_a_strictly_diabatic_electronic_basis_for_molecular_systems} 
	
	The most trivial method to achieve a diabatic representation from adiabatic is to introduce the \textit{crude-adiabatic basis}
	
	\begin{equation}\label{eq:2.13}
		\psi_k(r,R)_{cr} = \sum_{l}\chi_{kl}(R)\phi_l(r|R_0).
	\end{equation}
	where $R_0$ is a reference point of nuclear geometry. Generally, $R_0$ is usually chosen to be the minimum of the conical intersection, as $R_0$ is a fixed point. For this ansatz the nuclear kinetic term $T_N$ no longer acts on the electronic eigenfunctions $\phi_l(r|R_0)$.
	
	Next, substituting $\psi_k(r,R)_{cr}$ into $(\ref{eq:2.2})$,  the molecular Hamiltonian takes form as
	
	\begin{equation}\label{eq:2.12}
		\begin{matrix}
			H(r,R)\psi_k(r,R)_{cr}  = E_k\psi_k(r,R)_{cr} =
			\\
			\\
			 
			\sum_{l}\phi_l(r|R_0) T_N \chi_{lk}(R) 
	
			+  \sum_{l}\chi_{lk}(R) H_e(r|R)\phi_l(r|R_0)    =

			\sum_{l}E_k\chi_{lk}(R).
			\\
		\end{matrix}
	\end{equation}
	Projecting  both sides of the equation on $\phi_m(r|R_0)^*$, one arrives at
	
	\begin{equation}\label{eq:2.15}
			\sum_{l}\Big[ T_N \delta_{ml}  + \bra{\phi_m(R_0)}H_e(R)\ket{\phi_l(R_0)}\Big]\chi_{lk}(R) = E_k\chi_{mk}(R).
	\end{equation}
	Here, $\bra{\phi_m(R_0)}H_e(R)\ket{\phi_l(R_0)}$ are matrix elements of the electronic Hamiltonian for a fixed nuclear geometry. Setting $V(r|R) \equiv V_{e}(r) + V_{eN}(r|R)+ V_{N}(R)$, we define the electronic Hamiltonian as 
	
	\begin{equation}\label{eq:diabatic}
		H_e(r|R) = T_e(R) + V(r|R) = H_e(r|R_0) -V(r|R_0) + V(r|R).
	\end{equation}

	Rearranging $(\ref{eq:diabatic})$ to the form below,  a useful representation of the electronic kinetic energy operator is obtained. This  allows for the separation of the electronic Hamiltonian $H_e(R_0)$ component from the fixed electronic potential energy  $V(r|R_0)$.
	
	\begin{equation}\label{eq:2.16}
		\begin{matrix}
			T_e(r) = H_e(r|R_0)-V(r|R_0)
			\\
			\\
			T_e(r) + V_{e}(r) +V_{eN}(r|R_0)  + V_{N}(R)
			-\big[V_{e}(R) +V_{eN}(r|R_0)  + V_{N}(R) \big].
		\end{matrix}
	\end{equation}
	Evaluating  the electronic Hamiltonian matrix elements, the fixed electronic potential energy surfaces are obtained in addition to a matrix containing the residual potential energy contributions
	
	\begin{equation}
		\begin{matrix}
			\bra{\phi_m(R_0)}H_e(R)\ket{\phi_l(R_0)}_r  ,
			\\ 
			\\
			\bra{\phi_m(R_0)} H_e(R_0) -V(R_0) + V(R)\ket{\phi_l(R_0)}_r, \\
			\\
			\epsilon(R_0)_l\delta_{ml}+  \bra{\phi_m(R_0)}\big(V(R)-V(R_0)\big)\ket{\phi_l(R_0)}_r.
		\end{matrix}
	\end{equation}
	 The residual contributions may be redefined as the diabatic potential matrix 
	
	\begin{equation}\label{eq:2.18}
		U_{ml} = \bra{\phi_m(R_0)}\big(V(R)-V(R_0)\big)\ket{\phi_l(R_0)}_r
	\end{equation}
	and  substituting $(\ref{eq:2.18})$ into $ (\ref{eq:2.15})$,
	the newly defined diabatic Hamiltonian is \cite{Introduction_to_Quantum_Mechanics-Time-Dependent}
	
	\begin{equation}\label{eq:2.19}
		\sum_{l}\Big[ T_N \delta_{ml} + \epsilon(R_0)_m\delta_{ml} + U_{ml}\Big]\chi_{lk}(R) = E_k\chi_{mk}(R).
	\end{equation}
	
	By redefining our ansatz of crude adiabatic basis, we have effectively transformed all non-adiabatic coupling effects into the off-diagonal diabatic matrix elements. Because the nuclear kinetic operator in $(\ref{eq:2.13})$ no longer acts on the electronic eigenfunctions, the singularity present in $(\ref{eq:2.9})$ is absent. An additional feature of the diabatic representation is the reduction in criterion needed for electronic potential energy surface degeneracy. In the adiabatic representation, degeneracies occur when electronic energies are equal, and off-diagonal non-adiabatic coupling elements are zero. While in the diabatic representation, only the energies must be degenerate.  
	
	The major drawback of using the crude adiabatic representation is the reliance on $R_0$. As we have fixed our nuclear geometry within the electronic eigenfunctions, an infinite number of individual electronic reference calculations are needed to map the dynamics of a single problem, which is practically impossible.\cite{Conical_Intersections,Introduction_to_Quantum_Mechanics-Time-Dependent} 
	
